## What Are Scenes?

As a game grows, managing its different states becomes a serious challenge. Without structure, you end up tracking mode with a pile of flags:

```js
let inMenu = true, inGame = false, isPaused = false;

function update(dt) {
  if (inMenu) { /* ... */ }
  else if (inGame && !isPaused) { /* ... */ }
  // This spirals quickly
}
```

A **scene** is a self-contained unit of game state. Each mode of your game is its own class:

- `MenuScene` — title screen, settings
- `GameScene` — the actual gameplay
- `PauseScene` — an overlay while gameplay is frozen
- `GameOverScene` — end screen, high score entry

### The SceneManager

`SceneManager` holds a registry of **init functions** — one per named scene. When you switch to a scene, it creates a fresh `Scene`, calls the registered init function to populate it with nodes, then starts the update loop. The previous scene is destroyed first if one is active.

```js
const sm = new SceneManager();

sm.register('menu', (scene) => {
  scene.addNode(new TitleLogo());
  scene.addNode(new StartButton());
});

sm.register('game', (scene, params) => {
  scene.addNode(new Level(params.level));
  scene.addNode(new Player());
});

sm.switchScene('menu');               // → creates Scene, runs init, starts loop
sm.switchScene('game', { level: 1 }); // → destroys menu scene, starts game scene

// In the game loop:
function tick(dt) {
  sm.update(dt);  // forwards dt to the current scene
}
```

`Scene` itself is never extended or instantiated directly — it is always created and managed by `SceneManager`.

## Setting Up a Scene

A `Scene` is a plain container for nodes — you never extend or instantiate it. Instead, you provide an **init function** to `SceneManager.register()`. When `switchScene` is called, `SceneManager` creates a fresh `Scene`, passes it to your init function, and starts the loop:

```js
sm.register('game', (scene, params) => {
  // Called once when this scene becomes active.
  // Populate the scene with starting nodes using scene.addNode().
  const player = new Player();
  player.position.set(300, 400);
  scene.addNode(player);

  const enemy = new Enemy();
  enemy.position.set(100, 100);
  scene.addNode(enemy);
});
```

There is no `start()` or `destroy()` to override on `Scene` — it is just a bag of nodes. All game logic lives in the nodes themselves.

### Adding and Removing Nodes Safely

Nodes can be added or removed *at any time*, including from inside another node's `update`. This is safe because of two internal queues:

- **`pending`** — nodes added during a frame are staged here and only enter `nodes` at the start of the *next* tick. This prevents a newly added node from being updated on the same frame it was created.
- **`pendingRemoval`** — nodes removed during a frame are staged here and fully destroyed at the start of the next tick. This prevents index-shifting bugs when splicing the live array mid-iteration.

```js
// Inside any SceneNode's update():
if (this.hp <= 0) {
  this.scene.removeNode(this);  // safe — deferred to next tick
}
if (this.canFire) {
  this.scene.addNode(new Bullet(this.position.clone()));  // also safe
}
```

### Removing a Node Also Removes Its Children

`removeNode` removes the target node **and all of its children**, recursively. You never need to manually clean up a subtree — removing the root is enough:

```js
const ship   = new ShipNode();
const turret = new TurretNode();
turret.setParent(ship);

scene.addNode(ship);
scene.addNode(turret);

// Later — removing ship also removes turret:
scene.removeNode(ship);
```

## Scene Nodes — The Building Blocks

Every object in your scene **extends** `SceneNode`:

```js
class Player extends SceneNode {
  constructor(startPos) {
    super();  // auto-assigns id, sets up transform
    this.name = 'player';         // optional name for findNode()
    this.position.copy(startPos); // place in world
    this.speed = 200;
  }

  start() {
    // Called once when node enters the scene.
    // The node is fully live here — this.scene is set.
  }

  update(dt) {
    // Called every frame. dt = delta time in seconds.
    this.position.x += this.speed * dt;

    if (this.position.x > 700) {
      this.scene.removeNode(this);   // remove self
    }
  }

  destroy() {
    // Called when removed. Clean up event listeners, etc.
    super.destroy();  // always call super — clears internal event listeners
  }
}
```

### Nodes Can Talk to Each Other

Every node has a `scene` reference, so nodes can interact with their siblings:

```js
// Find a node by name:
const hud = this.scene.findNode('hud');
hud.showDamageEffect();

// Spawn a child:
this.scene.addNode(new Explosion(this.position.clone()));
```

### Auto-incrementing IDs

`SceneNode._nextId` is incremented each time a node is constructed, so every node gets a unique numeric `id`. This is useful for debugging and for systems that need to track nodes by identity rather than name.

## Managing Scene State

When multiple nodes need to share data — score, lives, wave number, game phase — you need a single source of truth. The wrong place for that data is the `Scene` object itself (it is a plain container with fixed properties). The right place is a dedicated **state node**.

### SceneStateNode

Extend `SceneNode` to create a node whose only job is to hold scene-level data. It lives in the scene alongside every other node and can be found by type from anywhere:

```js
class GameState extends SceneNode {
  constructor() {
    super();
    this.name  = 'gameState';
    this.score = 0;
    this.lives = 3;
    this.wave  = 1;
  }

  // update(dt) can drive timers, phase transitions, win/lose checks.
  update(dt) {
    if (this.lives <= 0) {
      // Switch to game-over scene from within the state node.
      sm.switchScene('gameOver', { finalScore: this.score });
    }
  }
}
```

### Setting Up and Reading State

Add the state node **first** in the init function so it is live before any other node's `start()` runs:

```js
sm.register('game', (scene, params) => {
  scene.addNode(new GameState());   // always first
  scene.addNode(new Player());
  scene.addNode(new HUD());
  scene.addNode(new EnemySpawner());
});
```

Any node reads or writes state through `findNodesByType`:

```js
class Enemy extends SceneNode {
  destroy() {
    const [state] = this.scene.findNodesByType(GameState);
    state.score += 100;
  }
}

class HUD extends SceneNode {
  update(dt) {
    const [state] = this.scene.findNodesByType(GameState);
    this.scoreText = state.score;
    this.livesText = state.lives;
  }
}
```

### Why a Node, Not a Global

- **Scoped to the scene** — destroyed automatically with the scene; no stale state leaks between sessions.
- **Has a lifecycle** — its `update` can drive timers, check win/lose conditions, trigger scene switches.
- **Consistent access pattern** — every node reaches state the same way, through `this.scene`.

## Transforms — Position, Rotation, Scale

Every `SceneNode` has a **transform**: three properties describing where it sits in space relative to its parent.

```js
const node = new SceneNode();

// Position — Vector — where is the node? (default: (0, 0))
node.position.set(100, 200);

// Angle — number in radians — how is it rotated? (default: 0)
node.angle = Math.PI / 4;    // 45° clockwise

// Scale — Vector — how is it stretched? (default: (1, 1))
node.scale.set(2, 1);        // twice as wide, normal height
```

All three are **local space** — relative to the parent node. A node with no parent is in world space directly.

### Transform ≠ Drawing

`SceneNode` does not draw anything by itself. The transform just describes *where and how* the node exists in the scene graph. A renderer (which we will build later) reads these transforms to draw sprites, shapes, or whatever the node represents.

### Connecting Vectors to Transforms

The Vector class you learned in the first two lessons is the foundation here:

```js
// Move a node along its facing direction each frame:
const facing = Vector.fromAngle(node.angle);
node.position.add(facing.scale(speed * dt));

// Point a node toward a target:
const dir = target.clone().sub(node.position);
node.angle = dir.angle();
```

Every vector concept — `add`, `normalize`, `scale`, `angle()`, `fromAngle()` — will appear in transform logic.

## Events — SceneNode as an Event Emitter

Nodes communicate through `this.scene.findNode()`, but that creates tight coupling: the caller must know the exact name and API of every node it touches. Add more reactions — audio, achievements, save system — and the calling node keeps growing.

The event system inverts this: a node *emits* that something happened; interested nodes subscribe independently.

### on(type, handler) — Subscribe

```js
const enemy = new Enemy();

enemy.on('died', (event) => {
  console.log('Enemy died at', event.data.position);
  // event = { type: 'died', data: { position: Vector }, target: enemy }
});
```

The handler receives a `SceneNodeEvent`: `{ type, data, target }` — the event type string, the optional data payload, and the node that emitted it.

### emit(type, data) — Dispatch

```js
// Inside Enemy's update():
if (this.hp <= 0) {
  this.emit('died', { position: this.position.clone() });
  this.scene.removeNode(this);
}
```

All listeners for `'died'` on this node are called synchronously in registration order.

### once(type, handler) — One-time Listener

```js
enemy.once('died', (event) => {
  // Fires the first time 'died' is emitted — then auto-removes.
  achievements.unlock('first-kill');
});
```

`once` works exactly like `on`, but the listener removes itself automatically after its first call.

### off(type, handler) — Unsubscribe

```js
const handler = (event) => { /* ... */ };
enemy.on('attacked', handler);
// Later:
enemy.off('attacked', handler);   // pass the same function reference
```

Keep a reference to the handler function if you need to remove it — `off` matches by identity.

### Why Events?

With direct calls, the emitter must know all its receivers:

```js
// Tight coupling — Enemy must know about HUD, audio, achievements
const hud = this.scene.findNode('hud');
hud.addScore(100);
audio.play('enemy-death');
achievements.check('first-kill');
```

With events, each receiver subscribes on its own:

```js
// In Enemy — announce the fact, know nothing about who reacts
this.emit('died', { score: 100 });

// In HUD, Audio, Achievements — each subscribes independently
enemy.on('died', (e) => hud.addScore(e.data.score));
enemy.on('died', () => audio.play('enemy-death'));
enemy.on('died', () => achievements.check('first-kill'));
```

The enemy no longer knows or cares who is listening. New systems can react to the event without touching the enemy's code at all.

## Canvas API Basics

An HTML canvas is just a `<canvas>` element. All drawing goes through a **2D rendering context** obtained from it:

```js
const canvas = document.getElementById('game');
const ctx    = canvas.getContext('2d');
```

`ctx` is a `CanvasRenderingContext2D` — the object with all the drawing methods.

### Rectangles

The simplest shape. `fillRect` and `strokeRect` skip `beginPath`:

```js
ctx.fillStyle = '#3498db';
ctx.fillRect(50, 50, 100, 60);    // filled rectangle at (50,50), 100×60

ctx.strokeStyle = '#fff';
ctx.lineWidth = 2;
ctx.strokeRect(50, 50, 100, 60);  // outline only
```

### Circles

Circles use the path model — `beginPath`, `arc`, then fill/stroke:

```js
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.arc(200, 150, 30, 0, Math.PI * 2);  // center (200,150), radius 30, full circle
ctx.fillStyle = '#e74c3c';
ctx.fill();
```

### Lines

```js
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.moveTo(10, 10);   // lift pen, move to start
ctx.lineTo(200, 80);  // draw to this point
ctx.strokeStyle = '#fff';
ctx.lineWidth = 3;
ctx.stroke();
```

### Polygons

A polygon is a path with multiple `lineTo` calls and `closePath` to join the last point back to the first:

```js
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.moveTo(100, 20);   // tip
ctx.lineTo(160, 120);  // bottom-right
ctx.lineTo(40,  120);  // bottom-left
ctx.closePath();       // back to tip — closes the shape
ctx.fillStyle = '#f1c40f';
ctx.fill();
ctx.strokeStyle = '#e67e22';
ctx.lineWidth = 2;
ctx.stroke();
```

### Text

```js
ctx.font = '24px monospace';
ctx.fillStyle = '#fff';
ctx.fillText('Score: 100', 20, 40);   // text, x, y (baseline)

ctx.textAlign = 'center';
ctx.fillText('GAME OVER', 400, 300);

ctx.textBaseline = 'middle';           // vertical anchor
```

`fillText` draws filled text; `strokeText` draws an outline. `textAlign` accepts `'left'`, `'center'`, or `'right'`; `textBaseline` accepts `'top'`, `'middle'`, or `'bottom'`.

## Drawable — The Drawing Contract

`Drawable` extends `SceneNode` and adds two things: a `zIndex` number and a `draw(ctx)` method to override.

The contract is simple: **draw as if your node is at the origin `(0, 0)`, facing right, at scale `(1, 1)`**. The `Renderer` will move the canvas context to the correct world position, rotation, and scale before calling `draw()` — you never need to account for the node's location yourself.

```js
class Ship extends Drawable {
    constructor() {
        super({ zIndex: 0 });
    }

    draw(ctx) {
        // The context is already positioned at this node's world transform.
        // Draw at (0,0) — the Renderer handles the rest.
        ctx.beginPath();
        ctx.moveTo(20, 0);      // nose
        ctx.lineTo(-15, -12);   // rear-left wing
        ctx.lineTo(-15,  12);   // rear-right wing
        ctx.closePath();
        ctx.fillStyle = '#4ade80';
        ctx.fill();
    }
}
```

Notice: no `translate`, no `rotate`, no position math inside `draw()`. The shape is always described at the origin — it is the renderer's job to put it in the right place.

### zIndex — Draw Order

`zIndex` controls the draw order across all `Drawable` nodes in the scene. Lower values are drawn first, so they appear behind higher ones:

| zIndex | Typical use |
|---|---|
| `-1` | Background tiles, sky |
| `0` | Default — most game objects |
| `1` | Projectiles, particle effects |
| `2` | UI elements, health bars |

Drawables with equal `zIndex` are drawn in the order they appear in `scene.nodes`.

## render() — Step 1: Clear, Step 2: Build Layers

`Renderer.render(drawables)` is called once per frame. It receives a flat array of all `Drawable` nodes — typically gathered like this:

```js
function tick(dt) {
    sm.update(dt);
    renderer.render(sm.currentScene.findNodesByType(Drawable));
}
```

The method processes that array in three steps. Here are the first two.

### Step 1 — Clear the Canvas

If `clearColor` is set, `render()` fills the entire canvas with that colour before drawing anything. This wipes the previous frame:

```js
if (this.clearColor !== null) {
    this.ctx.fillStyle = this.clearColor;
    this.ctx.fillRect(0, 0, this.canvas.width, this.canvas.height);
}
```

Setting `clearColor = null` skips the clear — useful when you want to render on top of a CSS background or composite multiple passes.

### Step 2 — Group Drawables into Layer Buckets

Sorting the entire drawables array every frame by `zIndex` would be O(n log n). Instead, the renderer makes a **single pass** through the array and groups drawables into buckets by `zIndex` using a `Map`:

```js
const layers = new Map();

for (const drawable of drawables) {
    const key = `${drawable.zIndex}`;   // '0', '1', '-1', etc.
    if (!layers.has(key)) {
        layers.set(key, { zIndex: drawable.zIndex, drawables: [] });
    }
    layers.get(key).drawables.push(drawable);
}
```

After this loop, `layers` maps each zIndex string to a bucket object containing all drawables at that level, in their original scene order. A scene with 200 objects but only 4 distinct zIndex values produces just 4 buckets.

The buckets are then sorted ascending by `zIndex`:

```js
const sorted = [...layers.values()].sort((a, b) => a.zIndex - b.zIndex);
```

Sorting 4 buckets is far cheaper than sorting 200 objects, and insertion order within each bucket is preserved automatically.

## render() — Step 3: Draw Each Drawable

With the sorted buckets ready, the renderer iterates them from lowest `zIndex` to highest and draws every drawable inside each bucket:

```js
for (const layer of sorted) {
    for (const drawable of layer.drawables) {
        this.ctx.setTransform(this._computeMatrix(drawable));
        drawable.draw(this.ctx);
    }
}

this.ctx.resetTransform();
```

Two things happen per drawable:

**`setTransform(matrix)`** replaces the canvas context's current transform matrix with the drawable's world transform. After this call, the canvas origin `(0, 0)` lands exactly at the drawable's world position, rotated and scaled correctly. Drawing at `(0, 0)` in `draw()` therefore places the shape in the right spot on screen.

**`drawable.draw(ctx)`** calls the subclass's overridden method. The subclass draws its shapes at the origin — the transform does the rest.

Finally, **`resetTransform()`** resets the matrix to the identity after all drawables are drawn, leaving the context in a clean state for the next frame.

## Loading Images

Every sprite-based game needs images loaded before the game loop starts. The browser loads images asynchronously — you hand it a URL and it fires a callback when the file is ready. Doing this manually is awkward:

```js
const img = new Image();
img.onload = () => {
  // can finally use img — but we're nested inside a callback
};
img.src = 'assets/characters.png';
```

`loadImage` from `src/utils.js` wraps this in a `Promise` so you can `await` it:

```js
const loadImage = (url) => new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    const img = new Image();
    img.crossOrigin = 'anonymous';  // required for canvas drawImage
    img.src = url;
    img.onload  = () => resolve(img);
    img.onerror = () => reject('Failed to load image: ' + url);
});

// Usage:
async function init() {
    const img = await loadImage('assets/characters.png');
    // img is an HTMLImageElement, ready to pass to Spritesheet
}
```

### Loading Multiple Images in Parallel

`Promise.all` starts all loads at once and waits for every one to finish — much faster than loading them one after another:

```js
async function init() {
    const [characters, tiles, ui] = await Promise.all([
        loadImage('assets/characters.png'),
        loadImage('assets/tiles.png'),
        loadImage('assets/ui.png'),
    ]);
    // All three are ready — start the game loop
    requestAnimationFrame(loop);
}

init();
```

Always start `requestAnimationFrame` **inside** the `async` init function, after the `await`. Starting the loop before assets are loaded means the first frames draw nothing.

## Spritesheet — Atlas Layout

A **sprite atlas** (or spritesheet) packs many animation frames into a single image. One network request loads everything — far cheaper than a request per frame.

`Spritesheet` describes the layout without storing pixel data:

```js
const sheet = new Spritesheet({
    image:        characterImg,  // HTMLImageElement from loadImage()
    spriteWidth:  80,            // width  of each frame in pixels
    spriteHeight: 80,            // height of each frame in pixels
    columns:      3,             // frames per row
    count:        6,             // total valid frames
    margin:       0,             // gap between atlas edge and first frame
    spacing:      0,             // gap between adjacent frames
});
```

### getRegion(frame)

Frames are numbered left-to-right, top-to-bottom starting at 0:

```
┌──────┬──────┬──────┐
│  0   │  1   │  2   │  ← row 0
├──────┼──────┼──────┤
│  3   │  4   │  5   │  ← row 1
└──────┴──────┴──────┘
```

`getRegion(frame)` converts the index to a `SpriteRegion` — a `{ x, y, width, height }` rectangle on the source image:

```js
sheet.getRegion(0);  // { x:   0, y:  0, width: 80, height: 80 }
sheet.getRegion(2);  // { x: 160, y:  0, width: 80, height: 80 }
sheet.getRegion(4);  // { x:  80, y: 80, width: 80, height: 80 }
```

`margin` and `spacing` adjust the math for atlases exported with padding:

```js
// Atlas with 2 px edge margin and 1 px gap between frames:
const sheet = new Spritesheet({
    image, spriteWidth: 64, spriteHeight: 64, columns: 4, count: 8,
    margin: 2, spacing: 1,
});
// getRegion(1).x = margin + 1 * (spriteWidth + spacing)
//              = 2 + 1 * (64 + 1) = 67
```

## Animation & Animator

A raw `Sprite` with manual `region` assignment works for static images, but advancing frames by hand in `update()` is repetitive. `Animator` handles it automatically.

### Animation — A Named Clip

An `Animation` is a plain object: a unique `name`, an array of `SpriteRegion` frames, a frame duration in milliseconds, and whether it loops:

```js
const walkAnim = {
    name:          'walk',
    frames:        [0, 1, 2].map(i => sheet.getRegion(i)),
    frameDuration: 180,   // ms per frame
    loop:          true,
};

const attackAnim = {
    name:          'attack',
    frames:        [3, 4, 5].map(i => sheet.getRegion(i)),
    frameDuration: 120,
    loop:          false, // holds the last frame, then stops
};
```

### Animator — Driving the Sprite

`Animator` is a `SceneNode` (not a `Drawable`). Add it to the scene alongside the `Sprite` it drives:

```js
const sprite   = new Sprite({ sheet, zIndex: 1 });
const animator = new Animator(sprite);
scene.addNode(sprite);
scene.addNode(animator);

animator.play(walkAnim);
```

Each `update(dt)` tick, the animator advances its timer and writes the correct region to the sprite. No manual `update` needed in your own nodes.

### isPlaying(name)

`play()` always restarts from frame 0 — even if the animation is already running. Guard against redundant restarts:

```js
// Safe to call every frame in a state machine:
if (!animator.isPlaying('walk')) {
    animator.play(walkAnim);
}
```

### Events — 'start' and 'end'

`Animator` emits `SceneNode` events, so other nodes react without polling:

```js
animator.on('start', ({ data }) => {
    console.log('started:', data.animation.name);
});

animator.on('end', ({ data }) => {
    // 'end' fires only for non-looping animations
    console.log('finished:', data.animation.name);
    animator.play(walkAnim);  // return to idle
});

animator.play(attackAnim);
```

The `data` payload is `{ animation }`, so listeners always know which clip just started or ended.

## Camera in the Engine

Here is how the camera concepts land in the actual graphics.js code.

### The Camera Class

`Camera` extends `SceneNode` — it lives in the scene graph and inherits position, angle, and parenting. You can parent it to a player node for free-following, or move it directly.

```js
const cam = new Camera({
    viewport: { width: 320, height: 180 },
    zoom: 1,
});
scene.addNode(cam);

// Attach to a Drawable:
sprite.camera = cam;
```

All matrices (`_view`, `_proj`, `_projView`, `_invProjView`) are rebuilt automatically each frame by `cam.update(dt)`, which the scene calls for you. The getters `getViewMatrix()`, `getProjMatrix()`, and `getProjViewMatrix()` just return the cached results at zero cost.

### RenderLayer Key Includes Camera ID

Drawables with different cameras must be grouped separately — they live in different coordinate spaces even if they share the same `zIndex`. The bucket key now includes the camera ID:

```js
_getLayerKey(drawable) {
    return `${drawable.zIndex}:${drawable.camera?.id ?? ''}`;
}
```

### Camera Matrix Cache

`screenMatrix × projView` is identical for every drawable that shares the same camera. `render()` computes it once per camera in the first pass:

```js
const cameraMatrices = new Map();
const W = this.canvas.width;
const H = this.canvas.height;
setMatrix(this._screenMatrix, W, 0, 0, H, 0, 0);  // normalised → pixels

for (const drawable of drawables) {
    const cam = drawable.camera;
    if (cam !== null && !cameraMatrices.has(cam.id)) {
        cameraMatrices.set(cam.id, this._screenMatrix.multiply(cam.getProjViewMatrix()));
    }
}
```

`cam.getProjViewMatrix()` returns the pre-cached `proj × view` result. Multiplying by `_screenMatrix` gives the full normalised-to-pixel transform. One multiplication per camera per frame — not one per drawable.

### _computeMatrix() — The Final Combination

```js
_computeMatrix(drawable, cameraMatrices) {
    const pos   = drawable.getWorldPosition();
    const angle = drawable.getWorldAngle();
    const scale = drawable.getWorldScale();
    const cos = Math.cos(angle), sin = Math.sin(angle);
    const transformMatrix = new DOMMatrix([
        scale.x * cos, scale.x * sin,
        -scale.y * sin, scale.y * cos,
        pos.x, pos.y,
    ]);

    if (drawable.camera !== null) {
        const camMatrix = cameraMatrices.get(drawable.camera.id);
        return camMatrix.multiply(transformMatrix);  // (screen × proj × view) × world
    }
    return transformMatrix;   // camera = null → raw pixel coords
}
```

`ctx.setTransform(matrix)` is called with this result before each `draw()`.

## The Keyboard Event API

The browser fires `keydown` when a key is pressed and `keyup` when it is released. Both deliver a `KeyboardEvent`.

### e.code vs e.key

| Property | What it represents | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `e.code` | **Physical key** — position on the keyboard, layout-independent | `'KeyA'`, `'Space'`, `'ArrowUp'` |
| `e.key` | **Logical character** — the value produced | `'a'` or `'A'` depending on Caps Lock |

For game controls, always use **`e.code`**. A player on an AZERTY keyboard pressing the WASD position gets `e.code = 'KeyA'` — the same as QWERTY.

```js
window.addEventListener('keydown', e => {
  if (e.code === 'KeyW') /* move up — works on every layout */;
  if (e.key  === 'w')   /* breaks on non-QWERTY or with Caps Lock */;
});
```

### e.repeat

When a key is held the OS fires repeated `keydown` events. Guard against this for controls that should trigger once per press:

```js
window.addEventListener('keydown', e => {
  if (e.repeat) return;  // ignore OS key-repeat events
});
```

### Store Listener References

`removeEventListener` requires the **same function reference** used with `addEventListener`. Inline arrow functions are new objects every time — store them:

```js
this._onKeyDown = e => this._handle(e, 'start');
this._onKeyUp   = e => this._handle(e, 'end');
window.addEventListener('keydown', this._onKeyDown);
window.addEventListener('keyup',   this._onKeyUp);
// On destroy:
window.removeEventListener('keydown', this._onKeyDown);
window.removeEventListener('keyup',   this._onKeyUp);
```

## The Pointer Event API

`MouseEvent` models only a single cursor. On touch screens several contact points can be active simultaneously, and a stylus is a third input type. **Pointer events** unify all three:

```js
canvas.addEventListener('pointerdown',   handleDown);
canvas.addEventListener('pointermove',   handleMove);
canvas.addEventListener('pointerup',     handleUp);
canvas.addEventListener('pointercancel', handleUp);  // OS interruption — treat as pointerup
```

### Multi-Touch via pointerId

Every active pointer receives a unique `e.pointerId`. Track it to handle multiple simultaneous contacts independently:

```js
const active = new Map();
canvas.addEventListener('pointerdown', e => active.set(e.pointerId, { x: e.clientX, y: e.clientY }));
canvas.addEventListener('pointermove', e => {
  if (active.has(e.pointerId)) active.get(e.pointerId).x = e.clientX;
});
canvas.addEventListener('pointerup', e => active.delete(e.pointerId));
```

A mouse click also uses `pointerId = 1` — the same code handles both without branching.

### setPointerCapture

When a pointer is pressed and then dragged outside the canvas, `pointermove` stops firing. `setPointerCapture` routes all subsequent events for that id back to the canvas — essential for drag-based controls:

```js
canvas.addEventListener('pointerdown', e => {
  canvas.setPointerCapture(e.pointerId);  // must be called inside pointerdown
});
```

### Disabling Browser Touch Gestures

```js
canvas.style.touchAction = 'none';  // prevent scroll / pinch-zoom interception
```

## InputManager — Structure

`InputManager` is the central hub. It maintains four internal maps:

| Map | Key | Value |
|-----|-----|-------|
| `_controlStates` | `'device:control'` | `{ pressed, value }` — current physical state |
| `_controlToBindings` | `'device:control'` | `Binding[]` — bindings that involve this control |
| `_actions` | action name | `{ active, value }` — current action state |
| `_actionListeners` | `'action:type'` | `Set<listener>` — callbacks for each lifecycle event |

The constructor creates devices from a config object and registers them:

```js
constructor(config = {}) {
  this._controlStates     = new Map();
  this._controlToBindings = new Map();
  this._actions           = new Map();
  this._actionListeners   = new Map();
  this._devices           = new Map();

  if (config.keyboard) this._addDevice(new KeyboardDevice(this));
  if (config.pointer)  this._addDevice(new PointerDevice(this, config.pointer));
}
```

The config pattern keeps callers in control of which devices are active:

```js
const input = new InputManager({ keyboard: true, pointer: canvas });
```

`destroy()` forwards to every device so their DOM listeners are cleaned up:

```js
destroy() {
  for (const device of this._devices.values()) device.destroy();
  this._devices.clear();
}
```

## InputManager — addBinding & handleDeviceEvent

### addBinding

`addBinding` stores a binding and indexes it under **every control involved** — both the source and any required modifiers. That way, when any of those controls fires an event, the binding is found in O(1):

```js
addBinding(action, source, required = []) {
  const binding = { action, source, required };
  if (!this._actions.has(action)) this._actions.set(action, { active: false });

  for (const info of [...required, source]) {
    const key = `${info.device}:${info.control}`;
    if (!this._controlToBindings.has(key)) this._controlToBindings.set(key, []);
    this._controlToBindings.get(key).push(binding);
  }
}
```

### handleDeviceEvent — Four Steps

Every device calls this when a raw event fires:

**1 — Update control state:**
```js
const key   = `${event.device}:${event.control}`;
const state = getOrCreate(this._controlStates, key);
if (event.type === 'start')  { state.pressed = true;  state.value = event.value; }
if (event.type === 'change') { state.value   = event.value; }
if (event.type === 'end')    { state.pressed = false; }
```

**2 — Look up bindings** for this control (O(1) map lookup).

**3 — Evaluate each binding** — skip if this control is only a required modifier, then check all required controls are pressed:
```js
const isActive = state.pressed &&
  binding.required.every(ci => this._isControlPressed(ci));
```

**4 — Emit action lifecycle event** based on the previous and new active state:
```js
if (!wasActive && isActive)      this._emitAction(action, 'start',  value);
else if (wasActive && isActive)  this._emitAction(action, 'change', value);
else if (wasActive && !isActive) this._emitAction(action, 'end');
```

## InputDevice & KeyboardDevice

### InputDevice — Base Class

`InputDevice` owns the set of registered controls and routes events to `InputManager`:

```js
class InputDevice {
  constructor(manager, name) {
    this.manager   = manager;
    this.name      = name;
    this._controls = new Set();
  }
  registerControl(c)   { this._controls.add(c); }
  unregisterControl(c) { this._controls.delete(c); }
  emitDeviceEvent(control, type, value) {
    this.manager.handleDeviceEvent({ device: this.name, control, type, value });
  }
  destroy() { this._controls.clear(); }  // subclasses call super.destroy()
}
```

Controls register in `start()` and unregister in `destroy()`, tying their lifetime to the scene node lifecycle.

### KeyboardDevice — Step by Step

**Step 1 — Store listener references** in the constructor:
```js
this._onKeyDown = e => this._handle(e, 'start');
this._onKeyUp   = e => this._handle(e, 'end');
window.addEventListener('keydown', this._onKeyDown);
window.addEventListener('keyup',   this._onKeyUp);
```

**Step 2 — Remove them on destroy:**
```js
destroy() {
  super.destroy();  // clears _controls
  window.removeEventListener('keydown', this._onKeyDown);
  window.removeEventListener('keyup',   this._onKeyUp);
}
```

**Step 3 — Dual dispatch in _handle:**
```js
_handle(e, type) {
  if (e.repeat) return;  // guard OS key-repeat
  this.emitDeviceEvent(e.code, type, null); // feeds the action system
  for (const c of this._controls) c.handleKey(e.code, type === 'start');
}
```

The dual dispatch is intentional: `KeyboardDPad` must track four keys simultaneously to build a direction vector — that compound state cannot be expressed as a single device event.

## PointerDevice — Step by Step

`PointerDevice` introduces `_pointerOwners` — a `Map<pointerId, InputControl>` that records which control claimed each active pointer at start.

**Step 1 — Constructor: store refs, set touchAction, init map:**
```js
constructor(manager, canvas) {
  super(manager, 'pointer');
  this.canvas         = canvas;
  this._pointerOwners = new Map();
  canvas.style.touchAction = 'none';

  this._onPointerDown   = e => this._handle(e, 'start');
  this._onPointerMove   = e => this._handle(e, 'change');
  this._onPointerUp     = e => this._handle(e, 'end');
  this._onPointerCancel = e => this._handle(e, 'end');
  canvas.addEventListener('pointerdown',   this._onPointerDown);
  canvas.addEventListener('pointermove',   this._onPointerMove);
  canvas.addEventListener('pointerup',     this._onPointerUp);
  canvas.addEventListener('pointercancel', this._onPointerCancel);
}
```

**Step 2 — Destroy removes all four listeners:**
```js
destroy() {
  super.destroy();
  canvas.removeEventListener('pointerdown',   this._onPointerDown);
  // ... same for the other three
}
```

**Step 3 — _handle: two separate paths for start vs move/end:**
```js
_handle(e, type) {
  const rect = this.canvas.getBoundingClientRect();
  const pos  = new Vector(
    (e.clientX - rect.left) / rect.width,   // normalise to [0, 1]
    (e.clientY - rect.top)  / rect.height
  );
  if (type === 'start') {
    this.canvas.setPointerCapture(e.pointerId);
    const sorted = [...this._controls].sort((a, b) => b.priority - a.priority);
    for (const c of sorted) {
      if (c.handlePointer('start', e.pointerId, pos)) {
        this._pointerOwners.set(e.pointerId, c);  // record owner
        break;  // first control to claim wins
      }
    }
    return;
  }
  const owner = this._pointerOwners.get(e.pointerId);
  if (owner) {
    owner.handlePointer(type, e.pointerId, pos);
    if (type === 'end') this._pointerOwners.delete(e.pointerId);
  }
}
```

Routing move/end exclusively to the owner prevents two controls fighting over the same finger and avoids re-running hit-tests every frame.

## Controls & Screen-to-World

### InputControl — Scene Lifecycle

`InputControl` extends `SceneNode`. Its `start()` and `destroy()` hook into the scene lifecycle to register and unregister with the device automatically:

```js
start()   { this.device.registerControl(this); }
destroy() { super.destroy(); this.device.unregisterControl(this); }
```

### KeyboardDPad

Maps four keys to a `(-1..1, -1..1)` direction vector, tracking each key independently so diagonals work. Emits `start` / `change` / `end` based on whether the resulting vector is non-zero:

```js
this.vec.x = (this.states.right ? 1 : 0) - (this.states.left ? 1 : 0);
this.vec.y = (this.states.down  ? 1 : 0) - (this.states.up   ? 1 : 0);
if (!wasMoving && isMoving)  this.emitDeviceEvent('start',  this.vec.clone());
this.emitDeviceEvent('change', this.vec.clone());
if (wasMoving  && !isMoving) this.emitDeviceEvent('end',    this.vec.clone());
```

### PointerJoystick & Button — Screen Pixel Space

Both controls sit in **canvas pixel space** — `position` holds canvas pixel coordinates, not world coordinates. `_hitTest` converts normalised pointer back to pixels to compare:

```js
_hitTest(pos) {
  const px = pos.x * this.device.canvas.width;
  const py = pos.y * this.device.canvas.height;
  const c  = this.getWorldPosition();  // stored as canvas pixels
}
```

### Screen-to-World

`PointerPosition` converts normalised coords to world space by inverting the combined camera projection-view matrix — a single built-in `DOMMatrix` operation:

```js
screenToWorld(normX, normY) {
  const pv = this.getProjMatrix(W, H).multiply(this.getViewMatrix());
  pv.invertSelf();
  const pt = pv.transformPoint({ x: normX * W, y: normY * H });
  return new Vector(pt.x, pt.y);
}
```
